In [6]:
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=10, ncols=10, figsize=(10, 10))
for i in range(10):
    nums = train[train["label"] == i]
    X_num = nums.iloc[:, 1:].values
    y_labels = nums.iloc[:, 0].values
    for j in range(10):
        axes[i, j].imshow(X_num[j, :].reshape(28, 28), cmap="gray")
        axes[i, j].axis("off")
    axes[i, j].set_title(
        int(y_labels[i * 10 + j]),
        fontdict={"fontsize": 20, "fontweight": "bold", "color": "green"},
    )

We can see that some of the digits are so badly written that even a human will have problem understanding. Our model will have trouble understanding these images.

Preparing the Dataset¶

These are the steps we'll follow to prepare the dataset for our model:

  1. Create train test split
  2. Normalize the data
  3. Use array.ravel() to flatten the target array
In [7]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, test_size=0.1, random_state=42
)
X_train.shape, X_test.shape, y_train.shape, y_test.shape
Out[7]:
((37800, 784), (4200, 784), (37800, 1), (4200, 1))
In [8]:
X_train = X_train / 255.0
X_test = X_test / 255.0
y_train = y_train.ravel()
y_test = y_test.ravel()
y_train.shape, y_test.shape
Out[8]:
((37800,), (4200,))

ML Models¶

Making Some Functions¶

In [46]:
def evaluate_model(model, on="test"):
    if on == "test":
        data = (X_test, y_test)
    else:
        data = (X_train, y_train)
    y_pred = model.predict(data[0])
    accuracy = accuracy_score(data[1], y_pred)
    print("Accuracy:", accuracy)
    print("Classification Report:")
    print(classification_report(data[1], y_pred))
    cm = confusion_matrix(data[1], y_pred)
    cmp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(cm)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=((10, 10)))
    cmp.plot(ax=ax, xticks_rotation="vertical")
    performance_dict = {
        "accuracy": accuracy,
        "precision": precision_score(data[1], y_pred, average="weighted"),
    }
    return performance_dict
